{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_adderstongue_ver01/data/sn86075113/00415667048/1927022501/0449.xml":{"full_text":"NEWS OF SOCIETY\n\n\nMRS. MABEL KINNEY HALL, Editer\nTelephone 650-M\nWWWWWMWWWWVWW 1\nRappv Happenings\nSocial functions of the week are holding breath in deference\nto the season. Paying honor to the Lenten period, my lady finds\nit pleasant to keep out of the wet snow of the street crossings;\nand so, pleasant to stay at home. Anticipation of the sunshine\nand gaiety, that will brighten the coming weeks, adds glamour\nto present gatherings; while the landscape turns for.\nONE MORE SNOOZE\nOne more snooze,\" old Earth would use,\nEre setting forth on spring-time's cruise;\nDreamily making sweet reviews\nOf joy, that grows 'neath heavenly blues.\nEarth now pays a few brief dues\nTo laws of living, growing clues.\nWith throbbing heart, Earth bravely woos\nThe love of mad-cap March to infuse.\nM\nit\nit\nMiss Wylie Hostess,\nMiss Frances Wylie was hostess at\nher home on West Olive street, last\nFriday evening, at the close of the\nreception held by Pi Beta Phi soror\nity. Her guests, the Misses Lenore\nSullivan, Claudine Updyke, and Eliza\nbeth Gardiner, each with an escort,\nenjoyed a mid-night supper with roy\nal service.\nAt Dinner and Cards.\nMr. and Mrs. K. E. Torgerson en\ntertained a group of friends at din\nner, last Saturday evening, at their\nhome on West Lamme street. Messrs,\nand Mesdames George Baxter, Nelson\nFlint, C. H. Isbel, A. H. Lake, D. E.\nMoser, H. F. West, Dr. and Mrs. A.\nC. Kelly, and Mr. Paul Heidelman\nmade up the company seated about\nthe graciously served dinner table;\nand later enjoying the game of '500.\nW. R. C.\nWilliam English post of Women's\nRelief Corps held regular session,\nlast Saturday afternoon, with Mrs.\nMatt White in her place as president.\nInstallation ceremony was conducted\nfor two officers, who had been unable\nto attend the previous meeting of\nthe Corps. These were Mrs. L. S.\nThorpe, senior vice president, and\n5\nHow to Play\nBRIDGE\nV\nnew series cf lessons by\nWynne Ferguson\nAuthor of \"PRACTICAL AUCTION BRIDGET\nW\n*3\nJr\nS/J\nM\nCopyright 1926, by Hoyk, Jr.\nARTICLE No. 18\nIn a number of these articles, the\nwriter has pointed out that when a\nhand contains a singleton or void suit,\na suit bid is much preferable to a no\ntrump. The reason for this ia very\napparent. The opponents have the open\ning lead and it is almost a certainty\nthat they will lead your weak suit.\nAgainst a no-trump bid, a clever oppo\nnent will pass and open his strong suit.\nIf you bid a suit, however, he wilfover\nbid with his strong suit and you will\nthus gain valuable information: The\nmodern tendency is undoubtedly for\nsuit bids rather than no-trump. For ex\nample, suppose that, as dealer, you held\nthe following hand:\nHearts A, K, 10, 4\nClubs 7, 2\nDiamonds K, 9, 3\nSpades A, K, 10, 7\nShould you bid no-trump or one of your\nlour card suits? A modern up-to-date\nplayer would bid one spade and see\nwhat happens. If your opponents bid\nclubs, show your heart suit. If your\npartner bids clubs, bid no-trump. The\nobject of all sound bidding is to obtain\nthe best bid for the combined hands\nthat ia, of twenty-six cards, not thirteen;\nand the suit bids obtain that result\nmuch better than no-tn. np bids.\nThe following hands are instructive\nbecause they contain principles of bid\nding that occur very frequently. Study\nthem carefully until sure you under\nstand the principles involved.\nHand No. 1\nHearts K,\nI Y i Clubs\u2014A.K\nB Diamonds\nI 2 I Spades K\nNo score, rubber game. Z dealt and bid\none spade. A bid two diamonds and Y\npassed. What should B now bid? B has\na wide choice of bids. He ma y bid three\nclubs, two no-trump or pass in the hope\nthat his partner can make game in dis\nwriter is inclined to the\nlatter procedure. If A has a sound two\ndiamond bid, A-B should surely score\ngame, losing only one spade and one\nheart trick. It ia a very close hand.\nHand No. 2\nsound four card suit and one of five\ncards, bid the latter. Then if overbid,\nshow the four card suit, spades in this\ncase.\nHand No. 3\nI Y\nA\nBi\nz\n\nHearts A, K, 5, 4\nClubs \u2014A, K, 7,3\nDiamonds 10, 9, 3\nSpades J, 3\nNo score, rubber game. What should\nZ, as dealer, bid with the foregoing\nhand? In this example, Z has the choice\nbetween a four card major suit and a\nfour card minor suit. With\nonly four cards and each a sound bid,\nthe minor suit should be bid, rather\nthan the major. By so doing you an\nmuch more apt to get a bid from your\npartner than if you bid the major\nHe will try to take out a minor suit and\ntry to let you play a major suit. In this\nway you get more information by bid\nding one dob in this hand than ons\nheart. 11 overbid, show the heart suit.\na suit of\nsuit.\nBand No. 4\nHearts J, 9, 7,6,2\nClubs\u2014none\nDiamonds Q, 8,5\nSpades A, K, 9, 7,3\nY\n\u00ee\ns A\nB\nI Z t\n4\n10.9.7,2\nNo SCOTS, rubber game. Z dealt and bid\none heart, A two diamonds, Y two\nhearts and B three clubs. Z and A\nn am e d, Y bid three hearts and B bad\ntour dubs. Z now bid four hearts and A\ndoubled. What should Y do? Should ha\nredouble or pass? Y should pas* by all\nmeans. To redouble In this poansa\nwould be very bad judgment.\nHand No. 8\nmends.\nHearts\u2014A, 4\nClubs\u2014 A, K. Q, 7,4\nDiamonds J, 9.3,2\nSpades 9,8\nY I\nBi\nIA\nY I\nI Z I\nIA\nB I\nt z I\nNo score, tint game. Z dealt and bM\none heart. H A passed, what should Y\ndo? Should he also pass or should ha\nbid two dubs? Y should pass and show\nhit dub suit on the second round if ha\ngets the opportunity. To bid two dubs\nover one heart would deny the hearts\nbut a pass and then a bad of dubs,\nshows help for hearts and a big duo\nsuit. This is a common situ\u00e2t*\u00bb\nHearts\u2014K\nClubs K, 7, 6\nDiamonds A, Q, J,\nSpades-A, Q, J7f\nNo score, first game. What should 2, as\ndealer, bid with the foregoing hand? Z\nhas the choice of bidding one spade or\none diamond. The latter ia the better\nhad. When you have a choice\n10,4\nnuts carefully*\na\nMrs. W. Y. Smith, color bearer. Other\nmatters of business were conducted\nat the close of the installation.\nFor Methodist Choir Girls.\nMrs. B. B. Law arranged a delight\nful evening for the girls, who sing\nin the choir of the Methodist Epis\ncopal church, having them her guests\non Wednesday of this week. The\ntwenty girls met at 7:15 o'clock, in\nMrs. Law's home, and entered into\ntheir regular program of practice for\nnext Sunday's church music. At con\nclusion of the practice, there were\ngames and a supper, when four moth\ners joined Mrs. Law in serving good\nthings to eat.\nNewman Club.\nA February program was rendered\nby the Newman club, last Friday eve\nning at K. C. hall. Mrs. Martin\nGary, officer of the Catholic Women's\ncouncil, conducted the entertainment.\nThis included: a vocal solo, \"Then\nYou'll Remember Me\" by Valens\nJones, with Miss Virginia Gilbert\nplaying the accompaniment; \"Talk\non Washington\" by Thomas McCabe;\n\"Story of the Valentine\" by Miss El\nlen Cain in costume; vocal solo, \"I\nLove You Truly\" by Miss Sylvia\nColarchik, accompanied by Miss Gil\nbert; paper on \"Lincoln the Lawyer\"\nby Frank Kelly.\nKappa Delta Fire-Side.\nKappa Alpha Delta sorority en\njoyed last Saturday evening, with a\ngroup of friends gathered about the\nfire-side in the chapter house on\nWest Olive ^street. Twenty couples\nhad part in the visiting, the supper\nand dancing, that enlivened the eve\nning, with Mrs. Gregory, Mrs. Mc\nCall and Miss Kerfoot the chaperones.\nTwo house guests for the week end\nwere Miss Berthana Koontz from\nDillon and Miss June Burke from\nThree Forks.\nBethany Bible Class.\nMrs. Harris Kirk and Mrs. John\nWylie were hostesses for 22 members\nof the Bethany Bible class, last Fri\nday afternoon, at the home of Mrs.\nKirk on West Babcock street. The\nprogram was introduced by devotion\nal service, led by Mrs. G. W. Beatty.\nThere was also a descriptive story\nof the class, read by Mrs, Wylie; vo\ncal solos by Mesdames Bullock, Chris\ntianson, Yergey, Staats and Tedrick;\nand old-fashioned charades to add fun\nto the occasion. Refreshments were\nserved by the hostesses; then came\na short business session, during\nwhich an election of officers made\nMrs. C. N. Wood president of the\nclass; Mrs. Belshaw, vice president;\nMrs. E. P. Bullock, treasurer; and\nMrs. J. M. Wylie, secretary.\nPi Beta Phi Dartcing Party.\nThe annual dancing party of Pi\nBeta Phi sorority was an enjoyable\nfunction of last Friday evening, at\nTokio Village, with 45 couples as\nsembled. Col. and Mrs. C. R. W. Mor\nrison and Mr. and Mrs. S. C. Love\nlace, with Mrs. Cora Crockett, were\nchaperons; and the guests represent\ning other sororities were Janet Con\nkling from Alpha Omicron Pi, Lillian\nKindschy from Alpha Gamma Delta,\nRuth Casey from Kappa Delta, Edith\nur S from Chi Omega. Miss Evelyn\nBarton was also a guest from out of\nthe city. Peggy Howard and Jimmie\nPence made gracious attendants with\ndance programs and favors; little\nDorothy Smart rendered a dainty nov\nelty dance; and punch was served by\nEdith Waterman and Agnes Gary.\nThree Birthdays.\nIn the home of Mr. and Mrs. F. H.\nBenjamin, during the past week,\nthere were three happy birthday cele\nbrations. The sixth birthday of Jack\nBenjamin was honored on Thursday\nafternoon, with a company of ten lit\ntle friends, who played and\ngames\nhad share in the big birthday cake,\nwhich adorned the supper table. On\nSunday, it was the fifteenth birthday\nof Herman Benjamin, and the guests\nwere Mr. and Mrs. C. B. Swim and\ntheir son Palmer, seated about the\nelaborately served dinner table for\nthe celebration.\nThen, on Monday afternoon, Louise\nBenjamin celebrated the event of\neight years, with twelve little girls\nher guests. Games were played and\nan attractive supper served to add to\nthe good time.\nMurry-Spady,\nThe marriage of Miss Ruby Lillian\nMurry and Albert Phillip Spady was\nsolemnized on Wednesday evening, at\nthe home of the gfoom's parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. Spady, on West Main\nstreet. Rev. H. G. Klemme read the\nservice in the presence of twenty-two\nrelatives of the young couple, with\nMrs. Marie King playing the wed\nding march, Miss Stella Murry the\nbride's maid; and Charles King, best\nman. The bride i s daughter of Mr.\nand Mrs. E. E. Murry, who reside\nnorth of Bozeman, on the Mil' road.\nAmong those who came from a dis\ntance to attend the marriage service,\nwere Mr. and Mrs. George Spady,\nwho came from Stanford; and Mr. and\nMrs. William Spady and their little\nson from Hardy. Following the wed\nding supper, the young couple went\nto their newly-established home, at\ni-he corner of Ninth avenue and West\nBabcock street.\nA Music Recital.\nOn Saturday evening of this week,\nMrs. Mary Waters Houston will pre\nsent three of her younger pupils in\na piano recital. The program will be\ngin at 8 o'clock, in the mnsic room\nof the Y. M. \u00c7. A. building; and\nwhile the recital will be invitaitonal\nbecause of small seating\nfriends who may be interested, are\nasked to call Mrs. Houston by tele\nphone and so receive invitation.\nThe three pupils who will pl*y>\nJane Brotherton, Thelma Brown, and\nJune Houston, will be assisted by\nMrs. W. N. Purdy, who will sing two\ncharming children's songs. The foi\nlowing numbers will be rendered:\nall\nroom,\n\"Gondoliers''\n\"On a Quiet Sea\"\n\"The Grasshopper\" \u2014Gaynor Blake.\nPlayed by Thelma Brown.\n\"The Ghost in the Fire-Place\"\n\"Barcarolle\"\n\"The Nightingale\"\u2014Kullak.\nby Thelma Brown.\n\"To a Wild Rose\"\n\"From an Indian Lodge\"\n\"By a Meadow Brook\" \u2014MacDowelL\nPlayed by Jane Brotherton.\n\"Nursery Rhymes\n\"Ho! Mr. Piper!\"\u2014Curran. Sung by\nMrs. W. N. Purdy.\n\"The Pair\"\u2014Gurlitt_\n\"Rondo Capriccio'' \u2014Beethoven\u2014\n\"Arpeggio Waltz\"\u2014Grant-Schaeffer.\nPlayed by June Houston.\n\"On the Ice at Sweet Briar\"\u2014Craw\nford\u2014\n\"The Clown's Dance\"\u2014Hatch\u2014\n\"Joy Dance\"\u2014Crawford. Played by\nThelma Brown.\n\"Nodding Ferns\"\u2014Helm\u2014\n\"Songsters on the Boughs''\u2014Helm\u2014\n\"The Fauns\"\u2014Chaminade. Played by\nJane Brotherton.\nPlayed\nJJ\nW. C. T. U. Meeting.\nThe regular meeting of the W. C.\ni. U. was held at the home of Mrs.\nR. E. Bodley, 521 West Olive street,\nthe hostesses being Mesdames Clara\nBirch, W. C. Dawes, H. A Bolinger,\nand J A. Stafford. There was an un\nusually large attendance. Mrs. O.\nB. Van Horn led in the devotionals,\ntaking a lesson appropriate to\nances E. Willard day.\nrs. Willard A. Bell offered her\nresignation as secretary, as she is\nsoon to leave for an extended tour\nin Europe. Mrs. Ella Beatty kindly\nagreed to act in that capacity until\nV, 6 regular election. Mrs. C.\nWood reported the state executive\nboard meeting recently held in Hel\nena\nMrs. Birch, the president, spoke of\nthe recent poison alcohol scare. There\nhas never been a greater hoax, she\nsaid. The impression made by the\nNew York newspapers at Christmas\ntime was that drinkers died by the\nscore, deliberately poisoned by pro\nhibition enforcement officers, where\nas an official report shows but one\ndeath attributable to wood alcohol or\nany other d\u00e9naturant. The other\ndeaths were from quantity\u2014not from\nquality.\nconnected with prohibition,\" she said.\n\"Every government uses poison in\nalcohol to protect industry. Attempts\nof the cheaper style wet propagan\ndists to blame poison alcohol to the\ndry cause show -a lack of informa\ntion. Old soaks have for years died\nbecause of their addiction to wood\nalcohol, hair tonic, horse liniment,\nvanilla extract, varnish and other li\nquors when they could not obtain\nwhiskey.\nThe program arranged by Mrs. J.\nA. Shadoan, peace superintendent, and\nMrs. E. W. Thompson, medal contest\nDenatured alcohol is not\nff\ncontest in reading, the contestants\nbeing Mesdames P. W. Kately, S. A.\nHarper, J. B. Thomas, William Ginn\nand Willard A. Bell. Mrs. Harper\nwas declared the winner of the med\nal, for which she graciously thanked\nthe ladies.\nA buffet luncheon of hot waffles\nand coffee was served by the host\nesses and a social hour enjoyed.\nSidney Montana-Dakota Power\ncompany will build gas line from\nGlenive, 60 miles, and then 55 mile\nline to Williston. Also starts 72-mile\nsurvey for $576,000 Glendive gas line.\ni\na\nThe Community Players\ns\noffer for your approval\nY--\u00ab\n99\n44\n\nB\n6\ni\nI\na\nA Three Act Comedy\nto be presented\n\nS\nMARCH 7, 1927\nB\nat\na\nI\nThe High School Auditorium\nCurtain 8:15 sharp\nAdmission 75c\ns\n1\n\u00fcaiia(iBitaitaiiaitBnai<eiiiiiaita>iattstisiimt\u00abitau\u00abitsiiaitaiiaiiai{\u00abiisii\u00abiiS4taiisusitsi(Siiai!aitaiiotis\u00abt\u00abitmiaiMiiiaiiaiiSHatiaiiauaiiai:aiis,iatniiisiisiisiisitananB<iRi(itiBUBiisiiauai\nBanking and Currency\nThe underlying strength of the\ncredit situation today is primarily\ndue to the rapid growth of the bank\ning capacity of the United States in\nrecent years, states the current issue\nof the Guaranty Survey, published by\nthe Guaranty Trust company of New\nYork. The bank expansion during the\nlast four years has exceeded even the\ntremendous increase that was neces\nstry to finance the war. The loans,\ndiscounts and investments of state and\nnational banks and trust companies\nexpanded by more than $9,600,000,000\nbetween June, 1922, and June, 1926.\nDuring the same period the growth :n\ndeposits has been more than $9,500,\n000,000.\nSeveral factors contributed to this\ndevelopment, the Survey continues.\nThe heavy gold importations have\nswelled the bank reserves, while de\nposits have increased enormously\nfrom the savings of individuals and\ncorporations during the recent years\nof high business prosperity. The to\ntal amount of savings deposits in\nJune, 1926, was more than $24,500,\n000,000. This figure represents an\nincrease of $1,500,000,000 for the\nyear, whereas between 1912 and 1916\nsavings deposits increased only $1,\n000,000,000.\nThe banks are in a stronger posi\ntion than a year ago. Total borrow\nj n g 8 0 f the reporting member banks\nwere $44,000,000 smaller at the be\nginning of this month than on the\ncorresponding date in 1926. The Fed\nera i Reserve system has a vast reser\nvo i r 0 f credit at its disposal, which\nbe used to meet any reasonable\ndemand for commercial funds, to pro\nvide for any probable demand for gold\nfrom abroad without serious restric\ntion of the domestic supply and to\nprevent the occurrence of any severe\nfinancial embarrassment as a result\nof possible business recession.\nIn 1926 the dominant factoi in he\nmoney market were, first, economy in\nthe use of commercial credit as a i\u00bb*\n.\u00absac\nWj\ni\nta\n\nVa\nA\n\nTHRILL ofopenmgan ACCOUNT\nand~Cfio WISDOM\nThrill in seeing the little book with your name on it\u2014\nthrill in starting on the road that leads to success.\nWisdom in putting money where a momentary tempta\ntion can't reach it\u2014where it will bring more to you than\nyou put in it.\nGet that thrill!\nCommercial National Bank\nMEMBER FEDERAL RESERVE SYSTEM\ni \u00bb\u00bb\u00bb\u00abwmu i immtmmmmi x wtmwmtiwnnm i innmnotmtmwmm t m mw\nsuit of a declining price level, hand\nto-mouth buying, small inventories\nand record-breaking transportation\nfacilities; and, second, the very large\nresources of the Federal Reserve sys\ntem. Ait the opening of this year\nthere is no indication of a sudden or\ndrastic change in any of these factors.\nIt is reasonable, therefore, to sup\npose that money rates will remain\neasy at least in the near future.\ni\n\nTreasure and Rosebud counties sell\n$215,072 worth of alfalfa seed from\n1926 crop.\n\ntyncCMt\nm\u00e4y\u00fc\u00df\u00df&ui\nto-own, cun\u00c2,\ntum&cfauL\ncmpcntcuvb\ndbtcO\ncudAMUvtaqzf\nL. K. PENCE\n\nAUTHORIZED\nSALES AND SERVICE\nTelephone 210\nBOZEMAN, MONT.\nCIOM","height":"27648","width":"19536"}}
